The problem is your closing the server socket whenever you have a socket timeout exception. A socket timeout exception occurs when you have no responses in the specified time frame. You set the timeout to 5000ms, so if no one connects to the server it is closed. 

```java
try{
    // your code here
}catch (SocketTimeoutException e) { // &lt;-- This block of code runs when the timeout is reached
    // timeout exception.
    System.out.println(&quot;No requests yet.&quot;);
    ss.close(); // &lt;-- This closes the socket
}
```

You probably want to have two catch blocks. One will handle the case of a timeout, and the other will handle other exceptions. 
```java
try{
    DatagramPacket p2 = new DatagramPacket(indata,indata.length);
    // server receive  the packet from client 
    ss.receive(p2);
    System.out.println(&quot;Messge received.&quot;);
    // packet data convert in sting
    String s2 = new String (p2.getData()); 
    // print the received data on screen(console)
    System.out.println(s2);
}catch (SocketTimeoutException e) {
    // timeout exception.
    System.out.println(&quot;No requests yet.&quot;);
}catch (IOException e){
    System.out.println(&quot;Server Socket threw an exception!&quot;);
    e.printStackTrace();
}
```

