Local non-static variables without an explicit initialiser have _undefined_ value.  So initialisation is required when the value will be read before it is otherwise explicitly assigned.

It is possible to declare without initialisation, and then explicitly _assign_ a value before the value needs to be read. For example:

    int duplicates ;
    duplicates = 0 ;

But using explicit initialisation (i.e. assigning a value on creation of teh variable) closes the window during which the variable has undefined value. This can avoid bugs where you might read a variable before it has ever been assigned a value.  In that sense it is generally considered _good practice_ to initialise all non-static local variables.

The first thing the code does is _assign_ `firstNumber` (via `scanf()`)  so initialisation is not required, but would do no harm, and is often advised to avoid undefined behaviour.

`secondNumber` is tested for value _before_ it is assigned, so must have a value.  The test `secondNumber == -8` will be true on the first iteration.  The use of -8 seems arbitrary any negative value could be used, -1 would be more idiomatic.

Again `duplicates` is modified before it is assigned a value, and is a count of consecutive duplicates so must be initialised to zero.

The question says nothing about how the sequence is presented and can be generalised:

    int dupCount( int* seq )
    {
        int duplicates = 0 ;
        for( int i = 1; seq[i] &gt;= 0; i++ )
        {
            if( seq[i] == seq[i-1] )
            {
                duplicates++ ;
            }
        }
        
        return duplicates ;
    }

Example usage:

    int main()
    {
        int seq[] = {3, 11, 5, 5, 5, 2, 4, 6, 6, 7, 3, -1} ;
        printf( &quot;%d\n&quot;, dupCount( seq ) ) ;
        
        return 0;
    }

If arbitrary length user input is specified and simply omitted from your question, then:

    #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
    
    int inputDupCount()
    {
        int inp = 0 ;
        scanf( &quot;%d&quot;, &amp;inp ) ;
        
        int duplicates = 0 ;
        while( inp &gt; 0 )
        {
            int prev_inp = inp ;
            scanf( &quot;%d&quot;, &amp;inp ) ;
            
            if( inp == prev_inp )
            {
                duplicates++ ;
            }
        }
        
        return duplicates ;
    }
    
            
Usage example:
    
    int main()
    {
        printf( &quot;%d\n&quot;, inputDupCount() ) ;
        return 0;
    }

